Spectacular wingsuit jump over Bogota
Sportsman Jhonathan Florez jumped from a helicopter over Colombia’s capital Bogota on Thursday.
Equipped with a wingsuit (a combination with wings), it passed 160 km/h above the famous Monserrate sanctuary, located at more than 3,000 meters above sea level, where many badauds had gathered to observe its feat.
A black box in your car?
While U.S. road network planners struggle to find the money needed to repair the decaying highway infrastructure, many see a solution in the form of a small black box that attaches over the dashboard of your car.
The devices, which record all the miles traveled by a motorist and transmit the information to officials, are at the center of a controversial attempt in Washington and in government planning offices to reshape the obsolete system of funding major American roads.
The generally uninteresting sector of major-axis planning has suddenly provoked a lively debate and turbulent alliances.
Libertarians have joined environmental groups to lobby for the government to use the small boxes to keep track of the miles you travel, and eventually the road you travel, and then use the information to draft a tax bill.
The Tea Party has landed.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also very concerned and expresses its concern about the protection of privacy.
And while members of Congress can’t agree on whether to continue, several states haven’t waited.
They are looking at how, over the next decade, they will be able to move to a system that allows drivers to pay based on the number of miles traveled.
Thousands of drivers have already boarded these black boxes, sometimes equipped with a GPS monitoring system, for an experimental ride.
This is truly essential for our nation.
“It’s not like we have a choice,” said Hasan Ikhrata, general manager of the Southern California Association of Governments, which predicts the state will begin recording miles traveled by every California driver by 2025.
There will be a change in the way we pay these taxes.
Technology is here to do it.
The pressure comes from the fact that the country’s Highway Trust Fund, financed with taxes Americans pay at the pump, is financially dry.
Americans don’t buy as much gas as they used to.
Cars can travel more than miles with a gallon.
The federal tax itself, which is 18.4 cents per gallon, has not increased in 20 years.
Politicians are reluctant to raise the tax even by 1 cent, while gasoline prices are high.
“The gasoline tax is simply not sustainable,” said Lee Munnich, a transportation policy specialist at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently installed trackers on 500 cars to test a payment system by mile.
“This turns out to be the most logical long-term alternative,” he said.
Wonks calls this from user fees to mileage.
It is not surprising that the idea appeals to urban liberals, since taxes could be used to change driving habits in order to reduce congestion and gas emissions, for example.
California planners are interested in the system as they develop strategies to achieve the goals set out in the state’s ambitious global warming laws.
But Representative Bill Shuster (R-Pa.), chair of the House Transportation Committee, said he also saw it as the most viable long-term alternative.
Supporters of the Reason Foundation’s free market also appreciate the idea of charging drivers per mile.
“It’s not just a tax sticking in a big black hole,” said Adrian Moore, vice president of policy at the Reason Foundation.
People pay more directly for the benefits they receive.
The move is also backed by two former U.S. Transportation Secretary’s who, in a 2011 report, urged Congress to go down the path of paying by the mile.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that would have covered about 10,000 cars.
But the House presidency killed the proposal, responding to concerns from rural lawmakers representing voters who have to travel many miles every day to get to their work or to the city.
However, several states and large cities are making progress on their side.
The most determined is Oregon, which has mobilized 5,000 drivers to conduct the most important experience in the country.
These drivers will soon pay the state mileage fees instead of gasoline taxes.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is considering one.
Illinois is trying to test a limited number of trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes 17 agencies involved in road transport in states along the U.S. East Coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia, and Florida) is exploring how it could implement the change.
The concept is not a universal success.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer drivers recently equipped their cars with a device, drivers were concerned that the government could follow their slightest actions.
“Concerns about Big Brother and these kinds of things are a big problem,” said Alauddin Khan, who leads strategic performance management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It's not something people want.
At the start of the trial, the ACLU of Nevada warned on its website: “It would be relatively easy to turn these devices into full-fledged location devices.”
There is no need to build a huge and cumbersome technological infrastructure that will inevitably be expanded to keep records of people’s daily commutes.
Nevada is one of the few states that is now struggling to find affordable technology that would let the state know how many miles a car travels, but without knowing the exact place or time.
If we can do that, Khan added, citizens will be more comfortable.
Research into this technology has led some state agencies to call on a small California start-up called True Mileage.
Originally, the company was not meant to help motorists who pay taxes to states.
It was looking to break into the emerging auto insurance market, in which drivers would pay based on their mileage.
But the devices it tests have appealed to planners on the major axes because they don’t use GPS and provide a limited amount of information, periodically uploaded via modem.
“People will be more inclined to do this if you don’t record their speed and locate them,” said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
Major mistakes have been made in the pilot programmes of some States.
There are much less expensive methods and much less intrusive methods of proceeding.
In Oregon, planners try the experience by offering motorists different choices.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
They may still choose not to have a device at all, preferring instead to pay a plan based on the average number of miles traveled by all state residents.
Other states are hoping to sell the concept to suspicious citizens by allowing the devices to do more, rather than not enough.
In New York City, transportation officials are looking to develop a taxation system that would also be equipped to pay for parking fees, provide “pay-as-you-go” insurance, and create a real-time speed data set from other drivers that drivers could use to avoid traffic jams.
"Automobilists would be encouraged to participate because of the benefits the system offers them," said an urban planning paper.
However, some transport planners wonder whether the whole debate about mileage payment is not simply a huge diversion.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission’s San Francisco Bay Area, officials say Congress could very simply manage the bankruptcy of the Highway Trust Fund by raising gasoline taxes.
An additional single or annual tax could be imposed on drivers of hybrid vehicles and on others whose vehicles do not consume a lot of gasoline, so that everyone pays their fair share.
“There is no need for radical surgery when you simply need aspirin,” said Randy Rentschler, the commission’s director of legislation and public affairs.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of motorists will worry about protecting their privacy and a lot of other things.
David Bowie: Four Unreleased Listening
The British musician hasn’t finished surprising this year.
Starting with The Next Day, released in January, he concocted a luxury reissue scheduled for November 4, with several unreleased.
Four have already emerged on the web.
The announcement of the release of a new album by David Bowie had left everyone stunned.
On his 66th birthday, January 8, 2013, he announced that a new album would be released in March.
After ten years of silence (the last record, Reality, dated 2003) and too few public appearances, the English musician proved that one could still rely on him to sparkle the pop scene.
A feast for his fans
Not tired of surprises, David Bowie had more than one turn in his bag with The Next Day.
Thin White Duke will release the album again on November 4.
For the occasion, he concocted a real feast for his fans.
This reissue, titled The Next Day Extra, will feature three discs: the original album, unreleased studio sessions and remixes, as well as a DVD containing the four previously unveiled clips.
The Next Day Extra will contain a total of ten additional tracks compared to the original album: the three tracks from the Deluxe edition, five specially unveiled songs for the occasion, as well as two remixes.
David Bowie also made the presentations of this beautiful box in a video.
He introduces both each of the discs, but also the accessories provided with: exclusive photos and covers, a notebook to share his own impressions, a booklet with the lyrics...
And most importantly, it gives a taste of its new title Atomica, typically in the vein of The Next Day, with guitars very far ahead and rock electricity cleverly mastered.
Unpublished already listening
But Atomica is not the only title to reveal its charms.
The Informer, Like A Rocket Man, Born In A UFO are also available on the web.
The Informer is double-sided: a worrisome intro before a bright ride that gradually slows down to make way for a pop ballad.
On Like A Rocket Man, did Bowie want to make a little reference to Elton John’s Rocket Man, or even Gravity?
With this playful title, the singer seems at least in his element when he no longer has his feet on the ground.
Space Oddity, next door, was much more serious.
On Born In A UFO, David Bowie once again makes reference to his strangeness: would he come from another planet?
The bewitching guitar riffs make you want to leave the Earth.
Bowie has fun playing chameleon with these titles: turn informer, man aboard a rocket, Martian potential...
He hides and reveals at the same time, playing to adopt different personalities, as he has done throughout his career, including with his characters Ziggy Stardust and Aladdin Sane.
No wonder he has a mask in hand in the photograph of the Louis Vuitton Invitation to Travel campaign, whose new face he embodies.
It will appear in one of their commercials, aired from November 10.
Defence Minister Rob Nicholson insisted that the wounded soldiers were not summarily released from the Canadian Armed Forces, and stressed that a transition process was being followed by all soldiers before they returned to civilian life.
Attacked by Liberals and New Democrats in the House of Commons, Nicholson assured that prior to their release, members of the army were following a transition plan in collaboration with their superiors.
All wounded soldiers receive appropriate care for their return to civilian life and none of them are released before they are ready, he said.
Critics accuse the government of wanting to save money by not allowing injured military personnel - who do not meet the army's "universal service" rule requiring staff to be able to perform a variety of tasks - to reach the 10-year eligibility period required for retirement benefits.
They cited two cases reported by The Canadian Press, including that of a soldier released last Friday.
Corporal David Hawkins, a London, Ontario, reservist with post-traumatic stress disorder, has been released from the military despite his request to stay for another year in order to receive a fully indexed retirement.
His case came after Corporal Glen Kirkland, who told a parliamentary committee last month that he had been pushed out before he was ready because he did not meet the universality rule of the service.
Mr. Hawkins pointed out that a soldier could be prepared to leave, with plans and consultation sessions, but that this was totally different from wanting to leave the ranks.
“I told them I wasn’t ready,” he said in an interview with The Canadian Press on Wednesday.
I asked for months if there was a way for me to stay, and they said no.
Since the beginning of the major fighting in Afghanistan, the army has struggled to determine what latitude it can give to wounded soldiers who want to stay in the ranks but are not fit for combat.
Under current rules, seriously injured soldiers have up to three years to recover.
If they do not meet the criteria for deployments abroad, they may be forced to leave the military.
Data presented to Parliament last year showed that of the 1,218 soldiers released for medical reasons, 199 had not reached the required length of service to obtain retirement benefits.
Liberal veterans spokesman Jim Karygiannis on Wednesday called for the reinstatement of Corporal Hawkins, while New Democrat Jack Harris called for an immediate end to "this shameful practice."
Disney is betting on tablets to launch an animated series
US media and entertainment group Disney has decided to favor tablets over its own TV channels for the upcoming release of a new children’s series.
The first nine episodes of Sheriff Callie’s Wild West will be available from November 24 on watchdisneyjunior.com or via its app for phones and tablets.
Its worldwide launch on Disney Group channels is only scheduled for 2014, according to the release of its Disney Junior division.
The cartoon, intended for children from 2 to 7 years old, tells the adventures of the Callie pussy, sheriff of a city in the American West where she brings order with a magical lasso.
Each episode contains two 11-minute stories.
“Interacting with smartphones and tablets is second nature for children today,” said Albert Cheng, vice president of digital products at Disney/ABC Television Group.
This type of experience is part of Disney’s efforts to “extend the life of its series and build new relationships with its audience through digital platforms that are becoming increasingly important,” he added.
A survey published earlier this week by Common Sense Media showed an explosion in mobile device use by young children in the United States: 38% of those under 2 years old have already used a tablet or a phone, and 72% of those under 8 years old, compared to 10% and 38% two years ago, respectively.
Snowden is ready to ‘cooperate’ with Germany on US surveillance
Edward Snowden, the whistleblower for U.S. intelligence, said he was willing to go to Berlin to testify before the German parliament if the U.S. National Security Agency and its director Keith Alexander did not provide answers about their activities.
German MP Hans-Christian Ströbele met on Thursday with Mr Snowden in Russia, where he enjoys the right to asylum, to discuss his testimony in Germany.
In a letter the MP presented to the media in Berlin on Friday, Snowden said: “Although the result of my efforts was obviously positive, my government continues to treat the difference of opinion as a leak and seeks to penalize political discourse with accusations against which it is impossible to defend itself.”
However, telling the truth is not a crime.
In his letter, Snowden wrote that he believed that international support could persuade the U.S. government to drop criminal charges against him.
As part of the complaint filed by the U.S. Department of Justice, he is charged with espionage and theft of state property.
Hans-Peter Friedrich, Germany’s interior minister, told Zeit Online: “If Mr. Snowden is ready to speak to German officials, we will make it possible.”
Relations between the United States and Germany have been strained following complaints that the NSA had tapped German Chancellor Angela Merkel’s cell phone.
Thomas Oppermann, the MP who heads the parliamentary group overseeing foreign secret services, said that if there was a chance to hear Mr. Snowden as a witness “without putting him in danger and completely ruining relations with the United States,” it should be taken advantage of.
Mr Ströbele, a German Green MP, posted a photo of himself with Mr Snowden on his Twitter account.
During his visit to Russia, he was accompanied by two German journalists.
Mr. Ströbele said that according to the lawyer of the former NSA consultant, Mr. Snowden could not return to Russia if he left the country.
If Snowden testified in Germany, he would have to be assured that he would be “safe” there, the MP said.
Mr. Snowden wrote in his letter that he had been the subject of a “serious and sustained” persecution campaign that had forced him to leave his country.
However, he said he was encouraged by the global reaction to “my act of political expression.”
Citizens around the world as well as senior officials – including in the United States – have deemed the revelation of an inexplicable system of permanent surveillance to be of public utility.
The letter makes an offer of cooperation with the German authorities “when the difficulties of this humanitarian situation have been resolved.”
Cogeco Cable could soon offer interactive TV
Cogeco Cable subscribers may well have access to apps like Facebook, Twitter and ultimately the Netflix video-on-demand service via their TV in the not-so-distant future.
Cogeco’s subsidiary said on Thursday that it was currently conducting preliminary tests of the beta version of the platform with some of its users.
"This will allow us to showcase more user-friendly interfaces as well as more options," Cogeco President and CEO Louis Audet said in an interview.
Cogeco Cable thus follows its competitors, such as Bell, although the Cogeco subsidiary does not yet have a precise date in relation to this new platform.
"We have to adapt and change or resist change and fail," Audet said.
The ultimate goal remains to offer tools that our customers do not currently have access to.
Telecom giant Rogers has already indicated that it could offer Netflix if certain technical details, which have not been cited, could be settled.
In the United States, the popular video service says it is in discussions with some major cable providers so that its service is available through their streaming platforms.
Cogeco and Cogeco Cable CEO also welcomed the announcement made by the Harper government during his Speech from the Throne on October 16.
Ottawa wants to force cable and satellite TV providers to offer customers the ability to pay for services on a pay-per-view basis.
“We’ve been saying for about two and a half years that the idea of forcing consumers to buy large channel packages doesn’t work,” Audet said.
He hoped, however, that the consultations conducted by the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission (CRTC) would lead to interesting recommendations.
"These discussions will have to provide a new kind of frame of reference for defining our new Canadian cultural policy when it comes to television," said Cogeco's CEO.
The CRTC has been conducting public consultations since last week and is expected to continue with the industry this spring.
On the earnings side, Cogeco reported a net profit of $43.8 million in the fourth quarter, or 82 pounds per share.
This is a decline from net income of 44.9 million, or 83 pounds per share, from the same period last year.
The Montreal-based company explains this decline with depreciation costs linked to new acquisitions.
In 2012, Cogeco acquired the U.S.-based Atlantic Broadband cable company for $1.36 billion.
This was the first major acquisition of the company after the one that had failed in Portugal.
Last December, the Montreal-based company also purchased Peer 1 Network Enterprises, an Internet provider based in Vancouver, for $526 million.
As for Cogeco’s revenues, they grew by 41.5% in the fourth quarter to reach 504.7 million.
They are 1.8 billion for the current fiscal year.
The net profit of its main subsidiary, Cogeco Cable, was 43.9 million, or 90 pounds per share, down from 45.7 million, or 93 pounds per share, in the same period last year.
However, Cogeco Cable’s revenues increased by 45% to 470.4 million.
The company lost 15,237 customers in the fourth quarter.
However, for fiscal year 2013, the number of Cogeco Cable customers is up 5546.
Mr. Audet is not worried about the number of customers fluctuating in this way.
For me, this is not an indication of a trend change, he observed.
It varies from quarter to quarter with very strong competition.
From horse to beef products
Horse meat has been found in cans of beef products, sold by two small British retail stores at low prices, the food hygiene agency announced today.
Routine tests revealed that the products, developed in January in Romania and sold by the chains Home Bargains and Quality Save, contained horse DNA up to 1 to 5%.
“Because horse meat is not mentioned in the list of ingredients, it should not have been present in the product,” the agency said.
A scandal over the presence of horse meat in cooked dishes broke out in Europe earlier this year, following tests conducted in Ireland.
According to reviews by the European Commission, France was the country most affected by the presence of this type of meat in products supposed to contain only beef.
