Frontier Airlines plans to charge for hand luggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge up to $100 for passengers carrying hand luggage on its flights.
Frontier Airlines plans to start charging up to $100 for a carry-on bag and $2 for a coffee or soda, although in its announcement Wednesday, it indicated that passengers could take the unopened can with them as the plane descends.
The new hand luggage charges are for bags stored in the upper compartment, so small bags installed under the seat will always be free.
Frontier said it would charge $25 if fees were paid in advance and $100 if travelers only paid once at the gate.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O'Malley said the $100 was intended to encourage travelers to pay the fee in advance.
“We don’t want to pay that price,” she said.
Airlines began charging for first and second checked baggage in 2008.
Passengers trying to avoid these charges put as much as they could in hand luggage stored in the upper compartments, so there was often no room in those compartments.
These fees are one way to ensure that passengers carry fewer things on board.
O’Malley said the new fees won’t really be used to raise money.
It's about making Frontier's most loyal customers understand that it's becoming increasingly difficult to find room in the upper compartments.
Passengers who buy their ticket on the airline’s website will not have to pay.
Thus, a passenger queuing at a Frontier boarding gate could carry a bag for free, while the next person in the queue might have to pay $100 for a similar bag.
O’Malley explained that Frontier’s site and check-in procedures are changing to ensure passengers know about the charges before arriving at the gate.
Frontier hand luggage charges will not be applied until the summer, although no date has been set.
Passengers often rant about baggage and other charges, but airlines love them.
They believe that baggage handling costs are significant and that passengers who want this service should pay for it.
Many people on Wall Street consider the addition of baggage charges as a sign that airlines are paying enough to cover the cost of air travel after years of losses.
However, many of them did not pay the baggage fee.
Spirit Airlines Inc. applied the first hand luggage fee three years ago, and the low-cost airline Allegiant followed a little later.
The only other airline imposing such charges is Hungarian airline Wizz Air, said airline consultant Jay Sorensen, who closely monitors the surcharges.
He estimated, in a December 2011 report, that Spirit’s hand luggage fee was $50 million a year.
Sorensen, a former Midwest Airlines executive, recently traveled on Spirit and wondered what he would find at the boarding gate as passengers discovered the unusual hand luggage charges imposed by the airline.
“I’ve never seen such a smooth boarding procedure in my entire professional career,” he said.
I expected to see teeth grinning and a fight erupting at the door.
The plane was full, he added, “passengers got on board at lightning speed.”
Frontier also does like Spirit and charges a $2 fee for a coffee, tea, soda or fruit juice.
Frontier said passengers who drink a soda or fruit juice can take the unopened can with them, and those who drink coffee can be reserved for free.
They will always distribute water free of charge.
US Airways briefly attempted to charge for the drinks in 2008 but came back seven months later after passengers complained and no other major airline had followed.
Frontier’s decision to charge a hand luggage fee when passengers do not purchase their ticket directly from the airline is its latest effort to get customers to go to its site.
Airlines pay online travel sellers like Orbitz $10 to $25 for every ticket sold.
This has prompted all airlines to encourage passengers to buy directly from them instead of turning to an online travel agency.
However, Frontier has gone further in this area.
In September, it began offering only half of loyalty miles to customers who purchased their ticket through an online travel agency.
On Wednesday, she cut mileage premiums by 25% on a trip.
Thus, a 1,000-mile Frontier trip purchased from an online travel agency would earn 250 miles.
It also allows passengers to choose their seat in advance only if they purchase their ticket directly from the Frontier site.
Frontier has a loyal clientele in her hometown of Denver, but her business declines and she loses money.
Revenues fell 9% and its flight capacity declined nearly 13% in the first quarter, according to financial results released Wednesday by its parent company, Republic Airways Holdings Inc.
Republic tried to redress Frontier’s finances by selling the airline.
The NSA calls an “internal error” and not hackers for the failure of its site
The shadowy National Security Agency said Friday it was a bug that caused its public website to crash for a few hours, not hackers as some had claimed online.
“NSA.gov remained inaccessible for a few hours tonight due to an internal error that occurred during a planned update,” the spy agency said in an emailed statement.
The problem will be solved tonight.
Allegations that the breakdown was due to a distributed denial of service [DSD] attack are false.
Earlier this evening, online server trackers noted that the NSA site had been down for at least 6 hours, and some users still cannot access the site.
Earlier, an NSA spokesman told ABC News that the agency’s sensitive internal network was “not at all” compromised.
No classified information is at risk, the spokesman said.
At least one group of online hacktivists claimed to be responsible for the breakdown of the NSA site by a DSD attack.
DSD attacks aim to flood a targeted site until the servers are overloaded and the site collapses.
Cyber-tactics are not very sophisticated and attacks are not intended to penetrate the internal network of the targeted system.
The once ultra-secret NSA, once dubbed the “No Such Agency,” has been in the spotlight and heavily criticized in recent months following a wave of revelations about its vast communications surveillance programs at home and abroad – which are part of the NSA’s secret files stolen from the agency and leaked by former NSA consultant Snowden.
This growing controversy around the agency has sparked a lot of speculation that tonight’s incident was the result of a targeted cyber operation.
The Delta City Centre is now closed
The Delta Centre-Ville hotel closed its doors on Thursday in Montreal, after 36 years of existence.
The investment fund that owned the building sold it to developers who would turn it into student residences.
Three hundred and fifty people worked at the hotel.
Of these, 200 have not yet found a new job.
Delta vows not to let its employees down.
Employers came to meet employees directly on site, and the employees were met individually to assess their needs.
“This support will continue for the next six months,” said Félix Bisson, Delta Hotels’ Regional Director of Labour Relations.
The closure of the Delta is taking place in a very competitive hotel market.
The investment fund that owned this building had choices to make.
Either he reinvested in the building to continue operating it, so there were investments of tens of millions while the competition is very fierce, there are many new hotels that appeared in Montreal.
"Or he was selling it to someone else and that's what happened," says Paul Arsenault, holder of the Transat Tourism Chair at the UQAM School of Management Sciences.
Other hotels in Montreal will also be converted in the coming months, such as the Crown Plaza which will become a residence for the elderly.
In the meantime, four hotel projects totaling nearly 600 rooms will be launched within two years.
For the CEO of Titan, "the Goodyear Amiens purchase project starts with zero employees"
After throwing the sponge away in January for the partial takeover of the Goodyear site in Amiens-North promised to close, Maurice Taylor, the CEO of the American tyre Titan, declares, today, ready to save 333 jobs out of the 1,137 that the plant counts.
Arnaud Montebourg, Minister of Productive Recovery, had already announced this, Monday, October 21.
After giving up the project to buy the plant in January, you come back today.
You had uttered violent attacks and insults, speaking of “so-called workers,” who “work three hours” a day, of “crazy” unions, targeting the CGT.
We don't understand this turnaround.
Is that to please Mr. Montebourg?
I'm not trying to please anyone.
Except for my wife.
Mr. Montebourg is a charming young man trying to save some of the highest paid industrial jobs.
If I hurt someone with my words, I'm sorry.
But France also has a high level of tax and unemployment.
Does the truth hurt you?
Working seven hours a day when working eight hours in other countries handicaps France.
In India, China and many other countries, we work ten to twelve hours a day.
I have no prejudices about France.
What I see is a factory that makes good agricultural tires, has good equipment, is well located and has spaces to expand.
Why does Titan need this factory so much?
Titan doesn't need to buy this factory.
But, with a fair price and skilled workers, it’s worth a try.
What kind of deal do you expect between the CGT and Goodyear?
If, since the factory was announced, Goodyear had offered employees a good severance pay, I think 100% of employees would have accepted it.
Now let’s imagine that Titan buys from Goodyear the factory closed.
From then on, Titan could move the machines to Poland or any other European Union country that still has its own currency.
I think Mr Montebourg knows that.
