Bombardier's profit drops as aircraft deliveries and orders decline
Bombardier Inc, a Canadian aerospace and rail manufacturer, reported a 15% drop in its net profit on Thursday, under pressure from lower orders and aircraft deliveries in the third quarter and contract problems in its Trains division.
Bombardier, based in Montreal, has also failed to provide flight test data for its all-new CSeries aircraft or information on whether the aircraft will meet its ambitious commercial launch schedule by September.
After the inaugural flight of the test aircraft about a month and a half ago, it flew only three times, and then the question arose as to whether the test phase was on track.
Results did not live up to expectations and stock prices fell 8% on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
Cameron Doerksen, an analyst at National Bank Financial, lowered his rating on Thursday from “outperforming” to “sector performance” because of the low potential for the stock market to rise over the next quarter or two.
“Although the decline in aircraft deliveries was largely anticipated, we are really disappointed by the profit margin in the Transportation division,” Cameron Doerksen said in a note to customers.
We expect Bombardier to register new orders for its CSeries aircraft as the flight test program progresses.
However, if no new orders are announced in the coming months, we expect the market to become more skeptical about the program.
Bombardier hopes that the CSeries family of aircraft will be able to catapult it into the lower segment of a market now dominated by Boeing and Airbus.
The first test aircraft was unveiled in March and flew for the first time in September after months of delay.
But the number of firm orders for CSeries aircraft is modest so far at 177. It seems that potential buyers are waiting for the results of flight tests to validate the company's claims regarding the energy efficiency and savings potential of the new airliner.
At the moment, the company has registered a total of 403 orders and purchase commitments with 15 customers and operators.
Pierre Beaudoin, President and Chief Executive Officer, is confident that Bombardier will reach its goal of 300 firm orders before the commercial commissioning of the first aircraft.
Leaders also reassured analysts and the media on Thursday that the program was moving forward on schedule.
"The test aircraft did not stay on the ground any longer than expected," Beaudoin said in a conference call, adding that ground testing and software updates were planned during the plane's downtime.
Each constructor plans differently.
We decided to go on a first flight and plan for an update period, and that’s what we did.
This will happen throughout the flight program.
The second of the five test aircraft is expected to fly in the coming weeks, the others will follow shortly thereafter, the company said.
Yet analysts are skeptical that the first customer can fly a CSeries aircraft just 12 months after its maiden flight.
Bombardier said it was assessing the timeline for entry into service and will provide new information in the coming months.
“This slow flight testing – although apparently in line with Bombardier’s internal schedule – reinforces our view that entry into service will be delayed in the first quarter of 2015,” Doerksen said.
In the third quarter ended September 30, Bombardier’s net profit fell to $147 million, or 8 cents per share, from $172 million, or 9 cents per share, a year earlier.
Adjusted earnings per share remained unchanged at 9 cents.
