As a result, the revolt is raging, especially in France, one of the EU’s great leaders.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a means of controlling Germany and putting Paris on an equal footing with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a passport to its political legitimacy and has imposed its own economic policy in Europe, leaving the French economy struggling.
As a result, Marine Le Pen’s far-right party, the National Anti-European Front, has just won a crucial by-election, returning the Socialists to power in third place.
The Front National is now the most popular party in France with 24% of the vote – a timely warning for the British Labour Party that it cannot assume that a split on the right will automatically favor the left.
What does Marine Le Pen do with her new popularity with the French white working class?
It wants to use next year’s European elections to create a single, anti-European anti-currency bloc in the European Parliament.
If the anti-European parties do well in these elections, which is very possible, such a bloc could control the European Parliament for the first time.
This is what I think: very soon, the anti-European and anti-currency sentiment unique in Europe will unite and will eventually kill the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will return to something that will more closely resemble the free “Europe of (sovereign) nations” privileged by General de Gaulle.
Germany and some of its satellite economies may retain the euro, but France and southern Europe will find their own currency.
I expect the United Kingdom to distance itself from this project, and I hope it will make its eyes soft in the United States.
However, Washington's growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will be left behind in the Atlantic.
What about Scotland in all this?
