At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics held this week in Orlando, Florida, pedo-endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these early physical changes are quite common among young Americans and represent a new standard.
“I spend a lot of time reassuring parents – in general, it doesn’t indicate a rapid evolution towards full puberty,” Kaplowitz said.
Obvious signs of development, such as breast buds, hair under the arms and in the pubic area, and body odors, appear earlier in girls.
But there has been only a slight advance in the age of the first menstrual period over the past four decades.
In the United States, the average age is 12 and a half, compared to 12 years three quarters in 1970.
“Once the breast begins to develop, it takes at least two or three years before the first menstrual period appears,” said Kaplowitz, also the author of “Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Coping with This Common Problem.”
Time is the most accurate test for how puberty will evolve.
There is debate about what constitutes the actual onset of puberty, but it is considered “early” when breast development is accompanied by sudden growth before the age of 8.
In most cases, development slows down or stops – this is something a pediatrician can follow closely.
A faster evolution may justify tests by an endocrinologist to rule out serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are treatments to delay the onset of the first menstrual period and prevent other consequences: premature aging of the bones that can slow down growth and a small size in adulthood.
Recommendations for drug and hormonal treatment are based on the child's age, developmental rate, growth rate, and affective maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is cautious about drugs but acknowledges that “controlling puberty can alleviate some behavioral problems and the feeling for girls to be different from others.”
The other big problem is understandable: Parents simply don’t want their very young daughters to have their periods.
“They fear the risk of pregnancy or even how they will handle hygiene issues,” Kaplowitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls a woman whose daughter had her first period at age 10.
