FAA: Air passengers can now use gadgets on board planes (but not make a call with their mobile phone)
Airline passengers will be able to use their electronic devices from door to door to read, work, play games, watch movies and listen to music – but not talk on their mobile phones – under the highly anticipated new directives released Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration.
But passengers should not expect immediate changes.
The speed with which the change will be implemented will vary from one airline to another, FAA Administrator Michael Huerta said at a news conference.
Airlines will need to prove to the FAA that their aircraft are complying with the new directives and that they have updated crew member training manuals and aircraft storage rules to comply.
The FAA said it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of electronic devices on their planes.
Delta and JetBlue are among the companies that have already submitted plans.
“Depending on the plan, we could approve expanded use of electronic devices very soon,” the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers must turn off their smartphones, tablets and other devices as soon as the aircraft doors are closed.
They are not supposed to turn them back on until the plane reaches an altitude of 10,000 feet and the commander gives his green light.
Passengers are supposed to turn off their aircraft when the plane descends before landing and not turn them back on until the plane has landed.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are properly protected from electronic interference will be able to allow passengers to use their aircraft during take-offs, landings and ground rolling, the FAA said.
Most new airliners and other aircraft that have been modified so that passengers can use Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, President of the Association of Professional Flight Attendants, said she was pleased with these changes.
“Once the new policy is implemented safely – and we will work closely with carriers for that – it will benefit everyone,” Glading said in a statement.
We are frankly tired of feeling like “room overseers” when it comes to this issue.
But it will still be banned from connecting to the Internet to surf, exchange emails and SMS or download data below 10,000 feet, the agency said.
Passengers will need to put their smartphones, tablets and other devices into airplane mode.
So there is still no Words With Friends, the Scrabble-style online game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011 when he was ejected at high noise from an American Airlines plane after refusing to turn off his device while the plane was parked at the door.
And heavier devices like laptops will always need to be stowed up as they could hurt someone if they flew through the cabin.
Mobile phones on board will also continue to be banned.
Regulatory power over mobile phones belongs to the Federal Communications Commission and not to the FAA.
FAA may lift ban on certain electronic devices during take-off and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national transportation safety expert on CBS News, said cell phones were still considered risky.
“Mobile phones are really a problem, not only because they could eventually create interference with navigational instruments, but because we know, according to the FCC, that they could disrupt mobile relay antennas if used on board,” Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee set up by the FAA to examine the issue recommended last month that the government allow wider use of personal electronics.
The pressure on the FAA has increased in recent years to ease restrictions on their use.
Critics such as Senator Claire McCaskill, D-Mo., argue that there is no valid security reason for these bans.
Restrictions are also increasingly difficult to enforce as device use has become ubiquitous.
Some studies indicate that at least one-third of passengers forget to turn off their aircraft, or do so deliberately.
The FAA began limiting the use of electronic devices in 1996 following reports of interference with navigation and communication instruments when passengers were carrying FM radios, the high-tech gadget of the time.
New airliners rely much more on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed to withstand electronic interference and approved by the FAA.
Airlines have been allowing their passengers to use Wi-Fi at cruising altitudes for several years.
Airplanes modified to accommodate Wi-Fi systems also better resist interference.
The vast majority of airliners are expected to allow wider use of electronic devices under the new directives, Huerta said.
Today's electronic devices typically emit much lower power radio transmissions than previous generations of devices.
E-book readers, for example, only emit minimal transmissions when turning a page.
But transmissions are stronger when devices download or send data.
Amazon.com is among those pushing for easing restrictions on passengers’ use of electronic devices.
In 2011, the company’s executives loaded a airliner of Kindle e-book readers and flew it to see if there were any problems, but there were none.
This has inspired members of the FAA Advisory Committee to have mixed feelings about whether or not the use of the devices poses a risk.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said he thought the interference from the planes was real, even though the risk was minimal.
Other committee members said that there are only anecdotal reports from pilots that indicate that the aircraft can interfere with the systems of an aircraft, and that most of them are very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA authorize pilots to ask passengers to turn off their aircraft during instrument landings in low visibility conditions.
A travel industry group welcomed the changes, calling them common-sense arrangements for travelers equipped with technology.
“We are pleased that the FAA recognizes that a pleasant passenger experience is not incompatible with safety,” said Roger Dow, President and CEO of the U.S. Travel Association.
