Is the European elite ready to do business with Britain?
The Business for Britain campaign was launched in April with the promise to bring businesses together and define what wealth and jobs creators want to see change in our relationship with the EU.
To do this, we commissioned the largest and most comprehensive survey of British business leaders and asked them what they thought of Britain, businesses and the EU.
YouGov surveyed more than 1,000 business leaders, globally representative of all sizes, sectors and regions of the UK.
The findings of the survey will come as a surprise to many.
We have found that the vast majority of companies are now looking to export outside of Europe, focusing on countries that are modernizing and expanding while EU states are stagnant.
They want to see the government prioritize new trade ties with countries like China, India and Brazil rather than getting stuck in the long and arduous process of reforming European institutional arcana.
When asked for their views on specific policy issues – ranging from monopoly regulation to product laws – the majority of business leaders believe that control of these key competencies should be returned to Westminster.
The single market has caused general dissatisfaction, with companies saying that the cost of the Brussels Regulation is disproportionate to the benefits of being part of the European trading area – 40% of large companies, traditionally the most pro-European, even agree.
Finally, and more importantly, our survey of business leaders revealed that a large majority wanted Britain to continue its efforts to change the treaty and develop a relationship with the EU based on trade and not politics.
This conclusion, which can be found in all major groups and companies of all sizes, shows that the corporate world insists on a “significant change” that restores power to the UK.
The stakes are high – succeeding in changing the treaty and better representing Britain’s interests would lead to a 16% rollover of votes in favour of keeping the country in the EU in a referendum.
The Prime Minister should not doubt for a moment: this survey shows that British companies support this plan to renegotiate the terms of Britain's accession to the EU.
It also shows that companies hope that the renegotiation will be a significant change in the current balance of power in favour of a return to the UK.
It is possible, and increasingly necessary, to better represent the interests of UK companies, as the euro area is moving towards a closer economic and fiscal union.
The priority must be jobs and growth in Britain and, as the findings of our survey show, for businesses this means refocusing on trade and a fundamental change in Brussels’ regulatory approach.
