How biometrics will invade our lives
Are you done typing passwords to access your smartphone or pay for purchases?
American, French and Japanese researchers predict a future where we will be recognized by the biometric sensors of phones and computers.
Bernard Didier, Morpho's deputy general manager, even believes that "the century will be biometric".
Only biometrics will ensure the identity of a person transacting in a universe as transversal and transnational as the Internet.
Privacy organizations confirm this craze for biometrics, but worry about it.
In 2011 and in France alone, the Commission nationale de l’informatique et des libertés authorized 774 systems for the recognition of fingerprints, the shape of the hand or the venous network of the hand in companies, administrations, canteens...
“Everyone can soon be identified, anywhere and anytime,” said Justin Brookman, head of consumer privacy at the Center for Democracy and Technology (CDT) in Washington.
The reasons for such optimism, in some, and pessimism, in others?
Biometrics will be based on new techniques that will enable new services to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most commonly used biometric data are fingerprints, the contour of the hand and the venous network of the palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its constraints.
“For example, some people who work in concrete have very damaged fingers and their fingerprints are illegible,” said Philippe Robin, technical director of identity at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection as well as the verification of the venous network and the contour of the hand presuppose a voluntary and precise gesture of the people.
It is both a security - one cannot capture this data without their knowledge - and a drawback: the procedure sometimes has to be repeated and therefore takes time.
As a result, research has been conducted for some twenty years on other approaches, such as recognition of the face or iris (the colored part of the eye).
By increasing the accuracy of sensors and computing capacity of computers required for data analysis, these techniques become operational.
Accuracy of facial recognition has increased tenfold over the past five years, says Cyrille Bataller, director of Accenture’s European R&D labs.
With our help, the UK and Holland have deployed automatic border crossings using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a moving face or iris.
“Today, we are conducting research on voice recognition or how to walk using sound sensors, but it takes a quiet environment,” said Sridhar Iyengar, director of security research at Intel Labs.
A unique and unfalsifiable marker, DNA also raises hopes and concerns.
“As the current state of knowledge, it can be considered the ultimate biometric data,” confirms Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, Director of Studies, Innovation and Foresight at the CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very long and very expensive.
NEC offers forensic police a suitcase costing 90,000 euros to analyze DNA samples at the scene of a crime and in one hour.
The uses of biometrics are divided into two groups: identification (recognizing one person among others) and authentication (ensuring that the person is who they claim to be).
The identification so far concerned the issuance of identity papers: we must compare the biometric elements (fingerprints, photo, iris) with the information that the state has on all citizens already registered.
This ensures that a person does not attempt to impersonate someone else.
This principle of comparison may have other applications.
NEC thus offers VIP recognition at the entrance of a hotel or a store.
“We are retrieving images from surveillance cameras and comparing them to photos of celebrities who are freely circulating on the Internet,” explains Dany Nassif, head of business development for biometric identification solutions at NEC France.
Another use: take a picture of a queuing quidam in a store, track its progress through facial recognition, and calculate the wait time.
Authentication initially concerned physical access (borders, protected premises, canteens...) or logical access (opening a computer).
More recently, the presence control was added.
"One biometric pointer avoids the phenomenon of the boyfriend pointing to another," explains Cyrille Bataller of Accenture.
But, more and more, authentication will also concern transactions, especially those made from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from some distributors by introducing his card and placing his hand on a biometric reader: this gesture replaces the keystroke of the secret code.
A similar technique is tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and in Angoulême by the company Natural Security in partnership with banks and retailers: when paying in-store with his credit card, the customer does not type his code, but introduces his finger into a reader that scans the veins.
The experiment is planned to last six months.
If it is conclusive, biometric readers could soon arrive at French merchants.
Tips to reassure users
There are three ways to make biometrics appealing to the general public.
The first is to explain that it can save time.
"If, thanks to biometrics, a customer stays in the box thirty seconds less, it is appreciable," explains the director of a large area.
The second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you custom options.
And finally, reassure by highlighting the precautions taken to protect databases.
“Fingerprints are stored on a first server; people’s identities are in a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure case, which is blocked if you try to move it,” said Philippe Robin of Thales.
But, due to the lack of in-depth research, it is impossible to know if these speeches really convince users.
Privacy experts, however, continue to be concerned.
“The advances in facial recognition, the multiplication of surveillance cameras and the huge amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr or Picasa, make me fear the worst: widespread surveillance,” said Andrew Patrick of the Office of the Privacy Commissioner of Canada.
