Scientists have just highlighted how a dog’s tail movements are related to his mood.
Previous studies had found that happy dogs moved their tail more to the right (from the dog’s point of view), while nervous dogs moved it more to the left.
But now scientists say dogs can detect these subtle differences and respond to them.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: “Everyone knows that in humans, the left and right sides of the brain are differently involved in stimuli that arouse positive or negative emotions.”
Here we tried to see what was happening with other species.
He added that just as in humans, in dogs the right side of the brain was responsible for movement to the left and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to the disordered tail movements of other dogs, the researchers followed animals watching movies featuring other dogs.
They measured the animals’ heart rate and analyzed their behavior.
It probably won’t be long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes to one side and sometimes to the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: “We presented dogs with films of other dogs – either a naturalistic version or a silhouette to avoid any other factors of confusion – and we were able to trade the tail movement and present it as going more to the left or to the right.”
When the animals saw an unexpressed dog move the tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog that moves the tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they spotted a tail diverting mainly to the left (again from the point of view of the dog stirring the tail), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think the dogs were deliberately communicating with each other through these movements.
Instead, he thinks dogs know by experience what movements they should or shouldn’t worry about.
He added: “If you repeatedly meet other dogs and notice that most of the time their tail movement to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and the right side leads to a less friendly attitude, you will react based on that experience.”
The researchers say the findings could allow owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand their animals’ emotions.
Canine behavior expert John Bradshaw, a visiting professor at the University of Bristol’s School of Veterinary Sciences, said this was not the first study to examine the importance of the left and right in the canine species.
Last year, a team at Lincoln University found that dogs turned their heads to the left when looking at an aggressive dog and to the right when looking at a happy dog.
And in another scientific study conducted by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said: “Dogs were easier going towards a robot dog when its tail was moving to the left rather than the right, instead of becoming anxious – the opposite of what appears in the Italian study.”
He said the differences could come from the fact that the dogs that participated in the different studies did not fully consider the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study on how dogs react to real dogs could be helpful, he explained.
“Although many elements, collected from different mammals, indicate that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be specified – and dogs are no exception,” he said.
However, given the ease with which their behaviors can be recorded, it probably won’t be long before we understand why their tail sometimes moves on one side and sometimes the other.
