Back in black and white for Marie Chouinard, who presents at Danse Danse her two new group choreographies: the first inspired by the inks and poems of Henri Michaux, the second inspired by the famous piano solos Gymnopedias de Satie.
An evening that allows you to see all the prism of Chouinard, from art to tics and from ink black to white.
A white screen serves as a background wall.
On the carpet, also white, in the immense space that is the Théâtre Maisonneuve, advances, in profile, thin as a line and dressed in black, a body.
On the screen, an ink by Henri Michaux is projected.
The body, a simple trait, takes its form.
And this shape will be that of the whole piece: a row of physical imitations of the drawings.
The dancers, fully dressed in black, only their hands and face uncovered, waiting on either side of the playing area, rush when the next spelling appears, embody it, run out.
This black and white game by Henri Michaux is done in solo relays, in unison group (a mass that does solo), in a large group of twelve solos where each performs its sign.
One thinks of "Glory of the Morning", where, in solo, Chouinard performed a series of choreographic tasks written on cartels, placed online in the foreground.
It is the same principle, giant PowerPoint version.
Here the music is loud, percussion and electric guitars.
The energy is high, the pace is always fast.
There will be a break when Carol Prior takes refuge under the dance mat, to deliver, micro in hand, without sobriety or restraint, a part of Michaux’s poem, monotonous and monotonous in the scream, and continues dancing.
And the music to leave, and the sequence to resume.
This loud and energetic discharge, long, if possible, ends up stunning and numbing.
As does the regularity of the visual rhythm.
There are a few beautiful flashes - image creation has always been a strength at Chouinard - like those swirling hair or those black fabrics that stretch the lines.
But the choreographic approach lacks composition.
We have the impression that the choreographer, instead of going to meet Michaux's work, has prevailed, with her tics.
The result: the bodies seem flat in front of the drawings.
Michaux’s inks, like Gestalt forms, open up a wider, more porous imaginary than dance.
Only the end, in the negative, with its dancers chopped by strobe light and white signs in a suddenly black theater, touches the magic.
The audience liked it, the welcome was warm.
Gymnopedia, after the intermission, is richer.
The stage is partly draped in grey, the dancers and a piano are covered with fabrics, like furniture in a neglected house.
On the piano, dancers turn around to play the scores.
Their clumsiness in music, touching, give a real fragility.
On stage, couples pass, in love duos, very sensual, even erotic.
Group work, small transition solos, moving ensembles, choirs, writing is less binary.
Buffons appear, also familiar to Chouinard, with a red nose, in very polarized male-female love parades.
Loves are carnassiers, fugitives or gamblers.
The gesture, the laughter and the little screams beautifully transpose the archaic, the grace and the ridicule of bodies in coitus, of beings that merge.
But the piece takes its real flight after salvation.
A clown comes back on stage when the audience leaves.
There, everything becomes permissible: the fourth wall falls, the universes explored overlap, the cabotin dancers descend among the spectators, gloss, smoke, short-circuit, play codes of applause, stretch the sauce in a cleverly calculated disorder that remains sensual.
Joy and madness perspire, and it is Chouinard's art there to contaminate the public.
