John Kerry admitted, unprecedentedly, that American espionage “had gone too far inappropriately.”
John Kerry indicated a softening of the United States' defensive attitude towards its surveillance programs by admitting, unprecedented fact, that on several occasions, the espionage "had gone too far inappropriately."
The Secretary of State also admitted that he, like Barack Obama, ruled over “autopilot” when a series of incendiary revelations from whistleblower Edward Snowden about NSA spying activities emerged.
The leaks put the U.S. government at the center of a diplomatic storm with its allies.
Speaking at an intergovernmental conference in London via video link, Kerry said: “It is undeniable that the President, myself and other members of the government have learned some things in autopilot mode because we had the opportunity, from the Second World War to the difficult years of the Cold War, and of course 9/11.”
He then became the first high-ranking member of the U.S. government to admit that U.S. espionage had crossed the line, but insisted that everyone’s rights had not been violated.
He said: “In some cases, it went too far inappropriately.”
And the President is determined to try to clarify and make it clear to people that he is now conducting a thorough review of these practices so that no one feels wrong.
I assure you that innocent people will not be abused as part of this process.
Kerry insisted, however, that the NSA was a force acting for the good and that its surveillance operations had saved many lives.
He added: “We live in a new world where people are ready to be blown up.”
There is radical extremism in the world that is determined to try to kill people, blow them up and attack governments.
What if you could intercept their communications and stop them before they act?
We did indeed prevent planes from falling, buildings from exploding and people from being murdered because we were able to learn the facts in advance.
Meanwhile, U.S. lawmakers will travel to Europe to address concerns about the alleged U.S. spying case and convince Europeans of the need to continue joint counter-terrorism efforts with the United States, the chairman of the Senate subcommittee on European affairs said Thursday.
Sen. Chris Murphy of Connecticut said he had spoken to members of the European Parliament and others this week and was concerned about the threats they had made regarding a possible withdrawal of anti-terrorist organizations due to the sense of frustration aroused by the National Security Agency’s surveillance.
“It’s really important for the protection of national security in the United States that Europeans stay by our side in mutual engagement in the fight against terrorism,” Murphy, a Democrat serving his first term and chair of the U.S. Senate’s European Affairs Subcommittee, said in an interview from Washington.
And I’m going to go to Europe to make them understand that we must continue to work together to fight terrorism, despite the anger caused by the NSA’s programs.
The press reports that the NSA has captured millions of communications in Europe, which has damaged relations with some U.S. allies, however the director of the agency said this week that it was inaccurate and that it was a misunderstanding as it concerned metadata that NATO allies had collected and shared with the U.S.
Other revelations came from documents leaked by Snowden that the NSA intercepted data and communications from German Chancellor Angela Merkel’s mobile phone and those of 34 other heads of state.
The director of intelligence, James Clapper, justified the espionage of the allies by stating that it was necessary and that it was a common practice on both sides.
In this atmosphere of turmoil, Murphy said his office was arranging a congressional trip, which is expected to take place this year, and he hoped the delegation would include members from both parties and from both chambers.
The names of other participating legislators should be revealed in the coming days.
He said the route remains to be defined.
Murphy said the purpose of this trip was to improve relationships, but also to show “affectionate firmness.”
He explained that European heads of state should be honest with their citizens about the type of spy programs they have been running for years.
“We can modify our surveillance programs to better protect the rights of Europeans, but they also need to understand that we are not the only ones in the world who are spying,” Murphy said.
Meanwhile, Kerry plans to travel to the Middle East and Poland this weekend to deal with the resentment generated by US strategies in Syria, Egypt and Iran, as well as by US surveillance activities.
