Australian woman appeals prison sentence in Thailand
A 21-year-old Sydney resident, sentenced to 15 days in prison in Phuket for falsely claiming to have been assaulted by a taxi driver, appealed the judgment and was released on bail.
Stevie Rochelle Bamford was first found guilty by a Phuket Province court on June 15 after telling Thai police that a local taxi driver, accompanied by two other men who controlled her, had assaulted her early on Sunday, June 10.
However, video surveillance footage later revealed that she had returned to her hotel safely after separating from her Australian boyfriend.
Phuket police questioned Bamford for two days before she confessed to having invented the story.
She was detained in a local police station cell prior to the court hearing.
Bamford was sentenced to 15 days in a low-security detention center on the outskirts of Phuket rather than a women’s prison.
This is the daughter of former Australian Rugby League player Peter Tunks, who called on Canberra’s foreign ministry to help his daughter.
Tunks told the Sydney Sunday Telegraph that the whole family was “extremely concerned” about her daughter’s well-being and wanted her to return to Australia.
“Obviously we’ve been through a stressful time, but we hope to bring her home safely as soon as possible,” Tunks said.
Bamford appealed the judgment and was released after a bond of 50,000 baht was paid.
In Australia, the press said that in the meantime, she was on holiday in the Krabi region of southern Thailand.
Thai judicial sources said Bamford was represented by a local Phuket lawyer, but warned that the appeal could lead to an increase in sentences of up to two years in prison and imprisonment in an adult prison.
However, after the recent murder in Phuket of Michelle Smith, an Australian travel agent, Thailand could also seek to restore its deteriorated image to tourists, which could lead to acquittal.
French police will arrest Anderlecht supporters who have come in other than with RSCA buses
French police have decided to put in place strict rules regarding the meeting of the Royal Sporting Club of Anderlecht against Paris Saint-Germain set Tuesday, said Marie Verbeke, the spokeswoman for the Brussels-midi police zone, on Friday.
Belgian RSCA supporters who want to go to this Champions League meeting will have to use the travel system set up by the RSCA.
"The bus convoy will be escorted by police from a former Rekem border post to the PSG stadium," the spokeswoman said.
The process will be the same for the return.
"If other supporters had an intention to go to Paris by other means, the French police prefecture has indicated that measures have been taken to make arrests or even police custody possible," Verbeke said.
Living together in French, the challenge of the Marguerite-Bourgeoys school commission
At the Marguerite-Bourgeoys school board, 62% of students have a mother tongue other than French.
This is what motivated a year ago a consultation with parents, students, teachers and education staff to reflect on ways to better integrate students who live on horseback between different cultures.
The school board has just unveiled its vision of "Living together in French".
For the past year, Vision Diversité has been working in schools to help students of all backgrounds discover common references that are not limited to the French language.
The discovery of neighborhoods, our architecture, our places are landmarks.
Great names of writers, of artists, whether they are of a strain or have come from elsewhere.
Who are our builders?
“So we’re creating projects so they identify with all of this,” says Aida Kamar, President of Diversity Vision.
Michel Venne, of the New World Institute, identified several challenges for the school board.
"On the transmission, for example, of what Quebec culture is, the feeling of belonging, the support to the staff in the transformations that we are experiencing, within the student clientele," he enumerates.
The Marguerite-Bourgeoys school board has created a research centre that will provide tools for teachers who sometimes also come from elsewhere.
Rachida Azdouz, from the University of Montreal, will be the scientific director.
Preparation to manage a class in a North American, Quebec context.
“Different pedagogical strategies are the real need,” she sums up.
Research will focus on inclusion from all angles: linguistic, academic, social and cultural.
